[h1]v0.1.8 - B42.19 rebase + off-road drag + per-wheel skid marks[/h1]

[h2]Per-wheel skid marks[/h2]

Skid marks now come from the actual rear wheels. Previously a single sprite at the vehicle centerline approximated both tracks via a dual-streak texture; with anything wider (pickups, vans, trucks) or narrower than a sedan that approximation read wrong, and on curves the four fixed sprite orientations turned a donut into a polygon. v0.1.8 reads each vehicle script's wheel offsets, transforms them per-tick to each wheel's world position via the vehicle's yaw, and stamps an omnidirectional soft mark at every wheel. Wide pickups get wide tracks, compacts get narrow tracks, circles trace as actual circles, and the marks visually anchor where the rubber actually is.



[b]Compatible with PZ B42.19.[/b] Necroid Java patches rebased onto the 42.19 pristine - all 5 patches applied cleanly.

[h2]Off-road drag fix[/h2]

User report: trucks and SUVs would barely get past ~40 km/h in 2nd gear off-road, with maxed OffroadGrip / OffroadFloor and minimum RollResistanceOffroad only helping a little.

Root cause: the off-road drag formula in [b]CarController[/b] had a speed-dependent term ([i]0.01F * absSpeed[/i]) that was [b]10x its on-road counterpart[/b]. Combined with the [i]mass * 1/eff[/i] multiplier for low-OffroadEfficiency vehicles (trucks, SUVs), drag compounded quadratically with speed and ate most of the engine torque past ~40 km/h on grass. Grip was not the bottleneck; drag was.

[b]Fix:[/b] halved the speed-dependent off-road drag ([i]0.01F[/i] -> [i]0.005F[/i]). The base term + mass + 1/eff multipliers still encode "off-road resists motion" - this just tames the per-km/h compounding so trucks and SUVs can cruise.

[h2]Surface-grip floor[/h2]

Belt-and-braces clamp: surfaceGrip is now clamped to >= 0.05F before being folded into gripFactor. Protects against a misconfigured published tire profile or sandbox combination pushing the value <= 0 (which would have inverted the gripLimit feed and pulled the car backwards). No effect under default configuration - defensive only.

[h2]Off-road grip tooltip rewrite[/h2]

The previous "Grip off-road" tooltip didn't say HIGHER = more grip, so users raising it weren't sure it was actually helping. New tooltip is explicit:

[i]"Off-road grip strength. HIGHER = more grip (less tire slip) on dirt, grass and gravel. Default 0.85 = moderate slip; 1.5 = near-paved feel. Does not change rolling drag - tune that via Rolling drag off-road."[/i]

[h2]Manual install[/h2]

The manual-install bundle is renamed [b]B42.19_Manual_Install/[/b] with freshly-compiled 42.19 .class files. Dedicated-server users must redo the manual install once for the 42.19 update. This single re-install carries both the version rebase AND the off-road drag fix - bundled deliberately so it's only one install dance, not two in the same week.

Single-player Workshop subscribers: nothing to do, just update.
